A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in Czech Republic is relatively advanced, our operators offering almost the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force classical operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTU (Czech Telecommunications Office), which has reported that the price of a text message was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, has also confirmed it.
Thus, following the last steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming charges regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators less expensive than in the country.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that is far above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvořák, President of the Czech Telecommunications Agency Council (ČTU), has stated several times that there was no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, he is chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with his own network apparently has no more chance (at the moment, he would find only difficult frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a significant price drop, to which the traditional operators should then also react.
However, even before the entry of riots such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those heard at home today were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have real success.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch, in Poland, of the virtual Mobilking operator.
In just six months, this operator managed to win over 100 thousand customers and become the country's fifth operator.
Let's add that behind Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which has, among other things, the U:phone in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, they need much less customers than a classic operator.
They are, indeed, exempt from construction, operation and maintenance costs of the mobile network, relatively high.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited supply of services.
For example, in Britain Tesco Mobile offers text messages at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, placed on an unusual target group can also constitute a good blow to advertising.
Indeed, this operator is specifically aimed at men.
"The true men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept could also be used in our home.
Miroslav Čepíký, Vodafone's spokesman, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
As far as it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic are not very encouraging.
Mobilking's launch will take place in other countries in our area," said Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that operators in the Czech Republic were, in any event, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do their best to ensure that a potential competitor does not appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would thus take a new step to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, has not been hiding its intention of launching a virtual mobile operator for a long time.
"We tend to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile.
And the sooner it'll be the better.
We have already negotiated this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have succeeded in moving forward in the negotiations," said the spokesperson of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
So the future may be promising.
According to non-official information, we may be able to welcome the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for the moment, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At this point, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared to other very specific markets.
For the time being, no subject provided for a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sršeň of the Press Department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile Martina Kemrová's spokesperson states in a rare agreement with the statement of O2: "We have not recorded for the moment a viable and bilaterally beneficial project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Instead, Vodafone directs his attention to the completion of the requests to obtain his own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepíký said regarding this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we think means the most inputs from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile Internet."
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator meant an increase in competition, would have led to a lower price and thus to a lower profit.
What, then, would it be good to facilitate the development of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know that they understand each other in the oven. The joke accompanying the creation of the U.S. is also a witness.
The biggest apparent pressure on ČTU, when the U:phone was created, was the one exercised by T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by information available to the public from the ČTU website.
Today, the U.S. phone is ready to use as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted in this regard: "Competitive competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
In view of the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would be subject, and especially its services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies appears to be disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of the ČTU, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Agency for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter adopted, in view of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator on the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached for the time being, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not given sufficient priority to classical operators," Kristián Chalupa, in response to our question from the Department of External Relations of the UOHS, said.
A statement thus made would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than misleading.
Moreover, Kristian Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country, where virtual operators are usually present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a lower price of mobile telephone services."
However, pressure in the sense of an honest functioning of the market and a price drop is not apparently part of the interests of the UOHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, if it really is a coincidence, is of course a question.
Similarly, a strictly identical fuel price for all service stations is likely to be due to the accident and the hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not noted, in this regard, signs of anti-competitive behaviour, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore none has an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market for virtual operators are probably missing even the telecommunications regulator," Chaloupa said.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the ČTU, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some law experts suggest a different view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained at each time.
And the mobile operator logically has the monopoly on his network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a particular segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for ÚOHS that three mobile operators are performing in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many stakeholders (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Retrieval of responsibility on the ČTU is a fairly common turn in communications, by which the ÚOHS washes the hands of the case.
We have already encountered this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent renewal of the Telecommunications Act did not bring about an extension of the ČTU's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised to improve the situation.
This is something that the representatives of the UOHS must know very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work
In other words, the operation of some sort of virtual pseudo operators, several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own mobile phone service price list, but the latter are only partially public.
In most cases, it is a matter of companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Personalized mobile phone services are offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms are generally only available to the electorate.
The magic tower consists of the fact that the company before the operator is a classic business client, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it obtains special price offers (and other).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you are saying happened, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions that we would consider and which could result in a conclusion of collaboration with the company in question," replied Martina Kemrová to our question regarding this problem.
However, it is not likely that an echo of such activity will not be achieved until mobile operators are responsible.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, there are thousands of customers.
No operator shall, however, oppose such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negotiable benefits, and, at the same time, by opposition to genuine virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepíký points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a percentage of negligible customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as regular customers of mobile operators."
That is precisely what should appear strange in the ČTU.
In addition, another question was raised at the UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UOHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to follow the operator's explanation, which claims that there is no idea what would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer the most expensive country
As we have mentioned many times before, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant decline in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, classical operators were increasingly, more or less, trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were almost the same - too small, or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It is precisely at this level that, in developed countries, regulatory bodies were involved, which did not defend the interests of mobile operators, but those of their clients.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they ended up obtaining the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are dealing with this issue in the way of a hot potato that is being decomposed by transmitting it to a close target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in their skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But let's not throw the stain after the cognac.
If the queue information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at our home, the Czech mobile market may be moving.
If one of the operators accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it would be difficult for the UOHS to remain indisposed to the rejection (to discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
