The Sutes demanded a referendum in the United States
In 1945, the Germans of the Sudets demanded that Shumava be integrated into the United States.
This is the result of a letter filed in the collections of the Jihočeská vedecká knihová (The Scientific Library of the South Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some German Sudettes groups allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This comes from, among other things, a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of Jihočeská vedecká knihovna.
The Germans of Český Krumlov ask in the letter the American president not to allow "shumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and we really want to be sure that the words declaring that American troops come into German territory not in oppressors and enemies, but in liberators," is written in the letter, signed "People, to whom the fate of the Shumava is at heart."
Since the accession to Czechoslovakia is not allegedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, indifferent attitude, incomprehensibility, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take into his hands the protection of the Shumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the 4 million inhabitants," says the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the President of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of Shumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the present knowledge of post-war history, appear somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of the Germans of the Sutes of the time.
While at least the Czech Germans had to question whether the question of their expulsion from the Republic would arise, very few of them had such an opportunity.
Some expected the United States and Great Britain to obtain a certain type of autonomy for the Sutes.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms it.
During the war, he was, as a German of České Budějovice, engaged in the Navy in the Baltic States.
At the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp in the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to see him to learn the Czech language.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," says Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Beneš Decrees, he would not be expelled from the Republic.
