Interview - Secure return of blood
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Hema-Québec became one of the world's most secure and effective blood suppliers.
And above all, he regained public confidence, which had been seriously broken by the blood scandal contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to highlight the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations that such a disaster should not happen again.
While Judge Krever was delaying his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to provide all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec started its activities, almost 38 per cent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field during the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said, before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile".
From its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of the disease of the mad cow, a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, have been seen in Europe, which has held the fort since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
It was then based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports that when we do not know it and that a serious disease can result from it, in the event of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, there are exclusion measures.
In April 1999, therefore, the blood of persons who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
However, a few years ago, it was demonstrated beyond a doubt that this disease was transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the principle of caution applied had meaning."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV testing technique appeared on the market: the nuclear acid tests (TAN) that directly detect in the donor blood the presence of the virus itself and not the antibody against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
The TANs have made it possible to shorten the mute period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, there has been a substantial reduction in the risk of some donors being infected without knowledge and not being able to detect them.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, a person of 12 million is at risk of receiving blood contaminated by HIV.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, this will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission occurs through a blood product.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says Hema-Quebec, head of management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
Hema-Québec must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary went on to point out that, in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Quebec must also provide sufficient supply.
"Necessity increases because the population is ageing.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need to be recharged in red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors, which averages only 3% of Quebec's blood donation."
However, any healthy person aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria may give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travel in a country where malaria is taking place, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we will be able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Poor people are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they grow older and can no longer give their blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but especially to hold them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today's life is so frowning, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving of his blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was already considered a biomedical waste is a rich blood in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the establishment of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we are expected to take more than a thousand per year.
We should start by offering them for strikes at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this blood collection program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to it," because Hema-Québec has no means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
