The psychology of overfill: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in neurological and economics at the University of New York have been able to update the neurological and economic bases of this behavior known and apparently irrational.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced from this type of competition, such as a sale to auctions on eBay, and that is why they prefer to pay too high a price.
These researches have tried to establish a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" with the help of sales to experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups was playing the loto, while the other group was participating in a gaming auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance process (IMMf), researchers analyzed the active brain areas of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the sale to auctions, the essential element of which is the overfilling of a third, the whole under the brain stem, called striatum, was moving intensively at the loss of the part.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "auto-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the escape from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial monitoring analyses.
Under these circumstances, three groups met with a partner in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they did so.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they were winning from the party, they would receive 15 additional dollars in reward.
While the third group received this $15 before the auctions, members of the group also lost this money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is that the emphasis was placed on one victory, while on the other, on failure.
By proving the neurologists' hypothesis, the players' team "against failure" were available at higher positions than those of the control group and the "for victory" group.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any already existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them did not explain the phenomena found in the sale of auctions except for the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only the methods of neurological imaging have helped to eliminate the contradiction between the two theories, now based on a third explanation." - Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economic Sciences at the University of New York, noted.
Hepatitis: When do we need to consult a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
A hundred miles is estimated to be the patients who carry the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles follow a treatment. This is because often the patients do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases are different.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, are mainly propagated in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g.: food or contaminated water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended in any way to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis A symptoms appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, in general, accompanied by a poor general condition, weakness, stomach discomfort and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and white of the eye a visible jaundice, the cells become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this pathology, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that according to estimates, only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it may lead to a cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not aware of the virus, because the pathogen destroys the liver cells in a subtle way. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: individuals who had undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, 200 million patients are diagnosed with chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advised to consult your doctor as soon as you notice symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected on time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
On 30 September, it is the world day of hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 by the organizations representing the world's four corners of the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to the cirrhosis of the chronic liver, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
