The smart car imitates the bourdon flights
What method would be best to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if it is not the simulation of an existing obstacle detector already in nature?
For example, that one of the bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC, which took place in Japan, burgundy bees gave the initial strategic idea to engineers at Nissan, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired auto-robot system, of type BR23C, which has been equipped with quality bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
In its flight, each bee constitutes its own oval-shaped space, which, in fact, looks much like our safe protective shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and the brand's technological public relations.
The eye to the face of the bee plays a key role, since it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the face-to-face eye, engineers have approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 metres before the BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the microprocessor, which transforms it into a avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any system currently existing, this avoidance process is entirely instinctive.
"If it wasn't so, the mini robot couldn't react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotized car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where the collision is considered inevitable for the moment.
All this process must reflect what the bee does to avoid the other bees.
The process must take place in an eyelid.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go upward, downward or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of endless combinations of bees to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotary movement, acceleration and slowing down as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini robot
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and with a higher concentration of energy, making them longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is primary, not data processing, and even less capacity to store.
This mechanism should only treat a few incoming signals per second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers. Thus, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
There is no need for memory of a capacity of giga-bytes, or even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards designing a technology for instant avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will enter serially manufactured cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be incorporated into the GPS satellite navigation system so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on its way.
