Industrial prices continued to increase
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent over the previous month, and 12.9 per cent over the month of August 2007 - reports the Central Statistics Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to the previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of the fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent over the previous month and by 3.2 per cent over the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices have progressed only to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent, compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industries were only slightly higher by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first of all, the production of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of footwear with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of raw plastic and chemical materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing sector of products and chemicals (1.6 per cent).
This has resulted in a deflation in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), in the manufacture of electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 per cent), and a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry have recorded an increase of between 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent an important weight in national industrial production, prices have risen by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the gas price established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, these are the prices of the oil processing sector that have experienced the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the manufacture of metallurgical products, an increase in prices of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the important area of food production, beverages and tobacco prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions have taken place in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the whole of the processing industry, prices have risen by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
The prices of electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7% of those of the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to the allocation of sectors, in August, these are the investment profit-initiating sectors that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials production sectors for subsequent transformation did not experience any change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the most significant increase in energy production and subsequent transformation materials (16.8%) was observed.
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured by 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-initiating sectors, there was a fall of 1.4 per cent.
Sales prices for exports from the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent in 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment fell by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
