Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema, the cities clear the historic halls.
Historic cinema rooms close up for the Multiplex.
"A city without cinema halls is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the performer Giuseppe Tornatore, well illustrates what is happening in the large Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalizing cinemas, with the birth of large multi-rooms, and the death of mono-room consumption in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that we find unmistakable and unmistakable; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, it is often historical and memory-sponsored places, "It's like one of my friends was missing, someone we know, with whom we shared a lot of road and so many emotions," observes the director of the New Paradise Cinema, a film that offered to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and who told the poem of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia of a way of living the cinema, can be lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean everything: these last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and these are the rooms of the main cities that paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, Emilie Romaine is headed by 82 single rooms, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that t is the first person responsible for their disappearance is the development of the multiplex, because these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 screens in Lombardy over the past five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has evolved irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it should still ensure the survival of those who already exist, because when a firm room in a city, these frequencies are not necessarily ready to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of credit for traders: the state's previous debt is about EUR 10 million.
It is shameful that, ethically and morally, the Government does not comply with existing laws.
Supporting the sector would require between EUR 16 million and EUR 18 million per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, concerned about these closures, has decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between Mary and Anec, the first of which in Italy, to defend and promote single cinemas in historic and peripheral centres.
The proposed regulations include tax facilities for mobile operators and benefits to the public: viewers will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and in certain parking spaces.
"This is an initiative that I am pleased to note," observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna putting in place other measures.
It is clear, however, that, in contrast to the superpower of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, since today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the SuperCinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Paradise Cinema" to which I have been thinking about for 10 years.
I've been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I've been in front of the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I've lived with so many shared emotions, I turn around from the other side to not see the black panels through the dust.
